'''David Ray Wilkerson''' (May 19, 1931 – April 27, 2011<ref name=cbn20110428>{{cite news |title=Rev. David Wilkerson Killed in TX Car Crash |url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/us/2011/April/Rev-David-Wilkerson-Killed-in-TX-Car-Crash/ |date=April 28, 2011 |publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]]}}</ref>) was an [[United States|American]] [[Christian]] [[Evangelism|evangelist]], best known for his book ''[[The Cross and the Switchblade]]''. He was the founder of the [[substance dependence|addiction]] recovery program [[Teen Challenge]], and founding [[pastor]] of the [[non-denominational]] [[Times Square Church]] in [[New York City]].

Wilkerson's widely distributed sermons, such as "A Call to Anguish", are known for being direct and frank against [[apostasy]] and serious about making the commitment to obey [[Teachings of Jesus|Jesus' teachings]]. He emphasized such Christian beliefs as [[God]]'s holiness and righteousness, God's love toward [[human]]s and especially [[Christian views of Jesus]]. Wilkerson tried to avoid categorizing Christians into distinct groups according to the [[Christian denomination|denomination]] to which they belong.

Wilkerson was killed in a head-on car crash in Texas on April 27, 2011.<ref name=cbn20110428/> He was 79.

==Early years==
David Wilkerson was born in 1931 in [[Indiana]]. He was the second son of a family of [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] Christian preachers, and he was raised in [[Barnesboro]], [[Pennsylvania]], in a house "full of [[Bible]]s". His paternal grandfather and his father, Kenneth, were ministers. According to Wilkerson's own testimony, he was [[Baptism of the Holy Spirit|baptized with the Holy Spirit]] at the age of eight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sermonindex.net/modules/mydownloads/singlefile.php?lid=15234&commentView=itemComments |title=You Need The Baptism Of The Holy Spirit by David Wilkerson |publisher=Sermon Index |date= |accessdate=2013-11-29}}</ref>

The young Wilkerson began to preach when he was about fourteen. After high school, he entered the Central [[Bible College]] in [[Springfield, MO|Springfield]], [[Missouri]]. The school was affiliated with the [[Assemblies of God]]. In 1952 he was ordained as a minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebratethewhole.net/saints/DavidWilkerson.htm |title=Kirk Estes - obituary |publisher=Celebratethewhole.net |date= |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref>

===Ministry===
Wilkerson married Gwen in 1953. He served as a [[pastor]] in small churches in [[Scottdale, Pennsylvania|Scottdale]] and [[Philipsburg, Centre County, Pennsylvania|Philipsburg]] in [[Pennsylvania]], until he saw a photograph in ''[[Life Magazine]]'' in early 1958 of seven teenagers who were members of a gang in New York known as "Egyptian Kings".<ref name="NYT">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/29/nyregion/rev-david-wilkerson-79-evangelist-dies-in-crash.html?_r=0|title=Rev. David Wilkerson Dies at 79; Started Times Square Church|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2013-11-29}}</ref><ref name="wilkersonpublications">{{cite web|last=Wilkerson |first=David |url=http://www.wilkersonpublications.com/The-Cross-and-the-Switchblade-P6C2.aspx |title="The Cross and the Switchblade" More Details |publisher=David Wilkerson Publications |date= |accessdate=2011-03-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507110817/http://www.wilkersonpublications.com/The-Cross-and-the-Switchblade-P6C2.aspx |archivedate=May 7, 2010 }}</ref> He later wrote that he felt the [[Holy Spirit]] move him with compassion and was drawn to go to New York in order to preach to them. On his arrival, Wilkerson went to the court in which the teenagers were being prosecuted. He entered the room and asked the judge for permission to tell them something, but the judge ejected him.<ref name="NYT"/> Upon leaving, someone took a photo of Wilkerson, who then became known as the Bible preacher "who had interrupted the gang trial".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/interview-brother-of-late-david-wilkerson-on-his-life-legacy-50023/ |title=Interview: Brother of Late David Wilkerson on His Life, Legacy |publisher=Christianpost.com |date=2011-04-28 |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref> Soon after this, he began a street ministry to young [[substance dependence|drug addict]]s and [[Gang violence|gang]] members, which he continued into the 1960s.<ref name="wilkersonpublications" /> He founded [[Teen Challenge]] in 1958,<ref Name="TChistory">{{cite web|last=|first=|authorlink=|coauthors=|title=History :: Teen Challenge USA|work=|publisher=|date=|url=http://www.teenchallengeusa.com/program/history.php|doi=|accessdate=2008-11-22|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090916161446/http://teenchallengeusa.com/program/history.php|archivedate=2009-09-16|df=}}</ref> an evangelical Christian addiction recovery program  in [[Brooklyn]] affiliated with the [[Assemblies of God]], with a network of Christian social and evangelizing work centers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acadc.citymax.com/page/page/2495014.htm |title=Teen Challenge's Proven Answer to the Drug Problem |publisher=Association of Christian Alcohol & Drug Counselors |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221065833/http://www.acadc.citymax.com/page/page/2495014.htm |archivedate=2009-02-21 |df= }}</ref>

Wilkerson gained national recognition after he co-authored the book ''[[The Cross and the Switchblade]]'' in 1962 with [[John and Elizabeth Sherrill]] about his street ministry. The book became a [[best-seller]], with over 50 million copies in over thirty languages, and is included in ''[[Christianity Today]]'''s "Top 50 Books That Have Shaped Evangelicals".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2006/october/23.51.html |title=The Top 50 Books That Have Shaped Evangelicals |work=[[Christianity Today]] |date=October 6, 2006}}</ref> In the book, Wilkerson tells of the [[Religious conversion|conversion]] of gang member [[Nicky Cruz]], who later became an evangelist himself and wrote the autobiographical ''Run Baby Run''. Nicky had been the leader of the "[[Mau Maus]]" gang, and he and his friend Israel Narvaez became Christians after hearing Wilkerson preach. In 1970, ''The Cross and the Switchblade'' was turned into a [[Hollywood]] [[film|movie]] starring [[Pat Boone]] as Wilkerson and [[Erik Estrada]] as Cruz.

In 1967, Wilkerson began Youth Crusades, an evangelistic ministry aimed at teenagers whom Wilkerson called "goodniks"—middle-class youth who were restless and bored. His goal was to prevent them from becoming heavily involved with drugs, alcohol, or violence. Through this ministry, the [[CURE Corps]] (Collegiate Urban Renewal Effort) was founded. In 1971, Wilkerson moved his ministry headquarters to [[Lindale, Texas]]. On September 22 he founded [[World Challenge (ministry)|World Challenge]], an organization seeking to promote and spread the [[Good news (Christianity)|Gospel]] throughout the world.{{https://worldchallenge.org/overview|date=May 2011}}

Wilkerson claimed that in 1986, while walking down 42nd Street in New York City at midnight, the Holy Spirit called him to return to New York City and to raise up a ministry in [[Times Square]]. He founded and became the pastor of [[Times Square Church]],<ref name=cbn20110428/> which opened its doors in October 1987. The church first occupied rented auditoriums in Times Square (Town Hall and the Nederlander Theater), before moving to the historic [[Mark Hellinger Theatre]] in 1989, in which it has operated ever since.{{https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Times_Square_Church&oldid=860084685|date=May 2011}}

Wilkerson did not preach in the name of any specific denomination. Instead, he focused on biblical preaching with the aim of encouraging people to seek God through a personal and deeper knowledge of [[Jesus Christ]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tscnyc.org/about_us.php |title=Times Square Church &#124; About Us &#124; David Wilkerson, Carter Conlon, Patrick Pierre, William Carrol, Teresa Conlon, Ben Crandall |publisher=Tscnyc.org |date= |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref> and the experience of the [[Holy Spirit]]. He said:

{{Quote|I am not preaching some denominational doctrine, This church does not belong to any denomination. We are not Assemblies of God, we are not Baptist, we're not Methodist, we're not Catholic. We're just Holy Ghost people believing this book [The Bible].<ref>[http://www.sermonindex.net/modules/mydownloads/singlefile.php?lid=15234&commentView=itemComments You Need The Baptism Of The Holy Spirit (4:49-5:8)]</ref>}}

Throughout his ministry, Wilkerson had contact with many other prominent Christian ministers, including [[Leonard Ravenhill]], who was his friend, and [[Ray Comfort]], whom Wilkerson met in 1992 after listening to a message called ''Hell's Best Kept Secret''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.livingwaters.com/helps/HellsBestKeptSecret.pdf |title=Hell's Best Kept Secret |publisher=Livingwaters.com |accessdate=2013-11-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102102754/http://www.livingwaters.com/helps/HellsBestKeptSecret.pdf |archivedate=2013-11-02 |df= }}</ref>

From the 1990s, Wilkerson focused his efforts on encouraging pastors and their families throughout the world to "renew their passion for Christ".{https://worldchallenge.org/ministries}}

Wilkerson and his wife Gwen moved to [[New York City]] at the inception of Times Square Church in 1987, and in 2006 began splitting their time between New York and Texas. They had four children and eleven grandchildren.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}

==Prophecies==
Wilkerson claimed to have received a vision in 1973 regarding the future of the United States, subsequently published in a book called ''The Vision''. Some of the subject areas of this prophecy were: "Worldwide recession caused by economic confusion"; "Nature having labor pains"; "A flood of filth and a baptism of dirt in America"; "Rebellion in the home"; and "A persecution madness against truly Spirit filled Christians who love Jesus Christ".{{cn|date=July 2017}}

On March 7, 2009 Wilkerson posted a message to his personal blog titled 'An Urgent Message' where he re-stated an earlier prophecy he had made concerning New York city: "For ten years I have been warning about a thousand fires coming to New York City. It will engulf the whole megaplex, including areas of New Jersey and Connecticut. Major cities all across America will experience riots and blazing fires". Wilkerson indicated that this would be part of a "earth-shattering calamity" affecting the whole earth, brought on by the wrath of God in judgement against "the raging sins of America and the nations". Regarding the timing of these events, he said: "I do not know when these things will come to pass, but I know it is not far off." <ref>{{cite web |title=What You Need to Know about David Wilkerson's 'Urgent Message' |url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2009/marchweb-only/111-11.0.html |date=March 16, 2009 | accessdate=2015-07-23 | publisher=Christianity Today}}</ref>

==Death==
On April 27, 2011, while driving east on [[US Route 175]] in Texas, Wilkerson crossed into the westbound lane and collided head-on with a [[tractor trailer]].  He was pronounced dead at the scene, just over a month from his 80th birthday. (According to a Texas Department of Public Safety representative, Wilkerson was not wearing a seatbelt at the time of the crash.<ref>https://www.people.com/celebrity/david-wilkerson-killed-in-car-crash/</ref>) His wife Gwendolyn was injured.<ref>{{Cite news
  | last =
  | first =
  | coauthors =
  | title = Evangelist David Wilkerson, Times Square Church founder, dies in car crash
  | newspaper = Pocono Record
  | location =
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =
  | date = April 28, 2011
  | url = http://www.poconorecord.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110428/NEWS90/110429728/-1/NEWSMAP
  | accessdate = }}</ref>

Gwendolyn Wilkerson died a year later, on July 5, 2012 from [[cancer]], at the age of 81.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldchallenge.org/about_david_wilkerson/dw_fullbio |title=Home |publisher=World Challenge |date= |accessdate=2013-09-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514044240/http://www.worldchallenge.org/about_david_wilkerson/dw_fullbio |archivedate=2013-05-14 |df= }}</ref>

